<chapter xml:id="chapter-logic-equiv" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Logical equivalence</title>


<section xml:id="section-logic-equiv-equiv">
<title>Equivalence</title>

<p><dl width="wide">

	<li xml:id="definition-logic-equiv-equiv-statements">
		<title>equivalent statements</title>
		<idx><h>equivalent</h><h>logical statements</h></idx>
		<idx><h>statement(s) (in logic)</h><h>equivalent</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>statement(s)</h><h>equivalent</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m> A \lgcequiv B </m></usage>
			<description> statements <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are equivalent </description>
		</notation>
		<p> statements <m> A,B </m> such that <m> A \lgcbicond B </m> is a tautology </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title><m> A \lgcequiv B </m></title>
		<p> statements <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are equivalent </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<claim>
	<title>Equivalence of logical statements</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>for equivalence of logical statements</h></idx>
	<idx><h>equivalent</h><h>logical statements</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>statement(s) (in logic)</h><h>equivalent</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>logical</h><h>statement(s)</h><h>equivalence test</h></idx>
	<statement><p>
		Statements <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are logically equivalent if <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> <em>always</em> have the same output truth value whenever the same input truth values are substituted for the substatement variables in each.
		That is, <m> A \lgcequiv B </m> if <em><m> A </m> and <m> B </m> have the same truth table</em>.
	</p></statement>
</claim>

<problem xml:id="wexample-logic-equiv-construct-conditional">
	<title>Testing logical equivalence</title>

	<statement><p>
		Demonstrate that the following are equivalent statements.
		<md>
			<mrow> A \amp \colon \quad \text{If it's nice outside, I will ride my bike.}     </mrow>
			<mrow> B \amp \colon \quad \text{It's not nice outside, or I will ride my bike.} </mrow>
		</md>
	</p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		Let <m> p </m> represent the substatement <q>it's nice outside,</q>
		and let <m> q </m> represent the substatement <q>I will ride my bike.</q>
		Then the equivalence we want to establish is <md>p \lgccond q \lgcequiv \lgcnot p \lgcor q</md>.
		We can analyze the truth tables of both statements in the same table.
		</p>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col right="minor" /><col /><col />
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m> p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot p \lgcor q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> p \lgccond q </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<p>
		We see that the two statements always have the same truth value in all rows of the truth table,
		so they are equivalent.
		</p>

	</solution>

</problem>

<note><p>
	<xref ref="wexample-logic-equiv-construct-conditional" /> shows that the basic conditional connective <q>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /></q> can be constructed out of the basic connectives <q>not</q> and <q>or</q>.
</p></note>

<problem xml:id="wexample-logic-equiv-negate-biconditional">

	<statement><p> Demonstrate the equivalence <m> p \lgcbicond q \lgcequiv \lgcnot p \lgcbicond \lgcnot q </m>. </p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p> Again we build a truth table, and see that the <q>output</q> columns for the two statements are identical. </p>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col />
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m> p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> p \lgcbicond q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot p \lgcbicond \lgcnot q </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

	</solution>

</problem>

<!-- OLD... is this an exercise or activity now?
\begin{tyu}
	Show that <m> p \lgcbicond q \lgcequiv (p \lgccond q) \lgcand (q\lgccond p) </m>.
\end{tyu} -->

<proposition xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-properties"><p>
	Logical equivalence has the following properties.
	<ol>

		<li>
			It is <term>reflexive</term>.
			That is, <m> A \lgcequiv A </m> is always true.
		</li>

		<li>
			It is <term>symmetric</term>.
			That is, whenever <m> A \lgcequiv B </m>, then also <m> B \lgcequiv A </m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			It is <term>transitive</term>.
			That is, whenever <m> A \lgcequiv B </m> and <m> B \lgcequiv C </m>, then also <m> A \lgcequiv C </m>.
		</li>

		<li> Every pair of tautologies is an equivalent pair of logical statements. </li>

		<li> Every pair of contradictions is an equivalent pair of logical statements. </li>

	</ol>
</p></proposition>

<exercise><p>
	Thinking in terms of truth tables, consider why each of the statements of
	<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-properties" /> holds.
</p></exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-logic-equiv-prop-calc">
<title>Propositional calculus</title>

<p>
Logical equivalence gives us something like an <q>equals sign</q> that we can use to perform logical <q>calculations</q> and manipulations,
similar to algebraic calculations and manipulations.
To enable us to do such calculations,
we first need a <q>tool chest</q> of basic logical equivalences to use therein.
</p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus">
	<title>Rules of Propositional Calculus</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>of Propositional Calculus</h></idx>
	<idx><h>propositional calculus</h><h>rules of</h></idx>

	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> A,B,C,E,U </m> are logical statements,
		where <m> E </m> is a contradiction and <m> U </m> is a tautology.
		Then the following equivalences always hold.
		<ol>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-tauts">
				<title>Rules involving tautologies</title>
				<idx><h>tautology</h><h>propositional calculus rules</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-tauts-disjunction">
						<m> A \lgcor U \lgcequiv U </m>
					</li>
					<li> <m> A \lgcand U \lgcequiv A </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-contras">
				<title>Rules involving contradictions</title>
				<idx><h>contradiction</h><h>propositional calculus rules</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li> <m> A \lgcor E \lgcequiv A </m> </li>
					<li> <m> A \lgcand E \lgcequiv E </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-duality">
				<title>Duality of tautologies and contradictions</title>
				<idx><h>duality</h><h>of truth/falsity</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li> <m> \lgcnot U \lgcequiv E </m> </li>
					<li> <m> \lgcnot E \lgcequiv U </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-dbl-negation">
				<title>Double negation</title>
				<idx><h>negation</h><h>double</h></idx>
				<idx><h>double</h><h>negation</h></idx>
				<p> <m> \lgcnot \lgcnot A \lgcequiv A </m> </p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-idempotence">
				<title>Idempotence</title>
				<idx><h>idempotence</h><h>of logical connectives</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li> <m> A \lgcor A \lgcequiv A </m> </li>
					<li> <m> A \lgcand A \lgcequiv A </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-commutativity">
				<title>Commutativity</title>
				<idx><h>commutativity</h><h>of logical connectives</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li> <m> A \lgcor B \lgcequiv B \lgcor A </m> </li>
					<li> <m> A \lgcand B \lgcequiv B \lgcand A </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-associativity">
				<title>Associativity</title>
				<idx><h>associativity</h><h>of logical connectives</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li> <m> (A \lgcor B) \lgcor C \lgcequiv A \lgcor (B \lgcor C) </m> </li>
					<li> <m> (A \lgcand B) \lgcand C \lgcequiv A \lgcand (B \lgcand C) </m> </li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity">
				<title>Distributivity</title>
				<idx><h>distributivity</h><h>of logical connectives</h></idx>
				<p><ol>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity-left-and-over-or">
						<m> A \lgcand (B \lgcor C) \lgcequiv (A \lgcand B) \lgcor (A \lgcand C) </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity-left-or-over-and">
						<m> A \lgcor (B \lgcand C) \lgcequiv (A \lgcor B) \lgcand (A \lgcor C) </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity-right-and-over-or">
						<m> (A \lgcor B) \lgcand C \lgcequiv (A \lgcand C) \lgcor (B \lgcand C) </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity-right-or-over-and">
						<m> (A \lgcand B) \lgcor C \lgcequiv (A \lgcor C) \lgcand (B \lgcor C) </m>
					</li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan">
				<!-- <paragraphs xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-para"> -->
				<title>DeMorgan's Laws</title>
				<idx><h>DeMorgan's Laws</h><h>for logical connectives</h></idx>
				<idx><h>Law</h><h>DeMorgan's</h><h>for logical connectives</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-not-or">
						<m> \lgcnot (A \lgcor B) \lgcequiv \lgcnot A \lgcand \lgcnot B </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-not-and">
						<m> \lgcnot (A \lgcand B) \lgcequiv \lgcnot A \lgcor \lgcnot B </m>
					</li>
				</ol></p>
				<!-- </paragraphs> -->
			</li>

			<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond">
				<title>Constructing the conditional and biconditional</title>
				<idx><h>conditional</h><h>construction from negation and disjunction</h></idx>
				<p><ol cols="2">
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-cond">
						<m> A \lgccond B \lgcequiv \lgcnot A \lgcor B </m>
					</li>
					<li xml:id="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-bicond">
						<m> A \lgcbicond B \lgcequiv (A \lgccond B) \lgcand (B \lgccond A) </m>
					</li>
				</ol></p>
			</li>

		</ol>

	</p></statement>

</proposition>

<remark><p>
	Each of these basic equivalences can be established with a truth table.
	See <xref ref="exercise-logic-equiv-basic-equivalences" />.
</p></remark>

<example><title>DeMorgan</title><p>
	Using <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-not-and">Rule</xref>
	of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" />,
	the following are equivalent statements.
	<ol>
		<li> The triangle can't be both right and equilateral. </li>
		<li> The triangle is not right or it is not equilateral. </li>
	</ol>
	To see how the rule applies,
	let <m> p </m> represent the statement <q>the triangle is right</q> and
	let <m> q </m> represent the statement <q>the triangle is equilateral.</q>
	Then the first statement above is <m> \lgcnot (p \lgcand q) </m>,
	while the second statement above is <m> \lgcnot p \lgcor \lgcnot q </m>.
</p></example>

<p>
Now we need some new substitution rules to enable us to use the rules of
<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" />
in logical calculations.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv">
	<title>Substitution Rules</title> <!-- [for equivalent statements] -->
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>Substitution</h><h>for equivalent statements</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Substitution Rule</h><h>for equivalent statements</h></idx>

	<statement><p><ol>

		<li xml:id="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-substatements">
			<title>Replacing a substatement by an equivalent one</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m> A </m> is a logical statement and <m> X </m> is a substatement of <m> A </m>.
			If statement <m> Y </m> is equivalent to <m> X </m>,
			then the new statement <m> A' </m> obtained from <m> A </m> by replacing substatement <m> X </m> by <m> Y </m> is equivalent to <m> A </m>.
			That is, if <m> Y \lgcequiv X </m> then <m> A' \lgcequiv A </m>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li xml:id="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-into-variables">
			<title>Substituting into a known equivalence</title>
			<p>
			Suppose <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are logical statements,
			each of which involves substatement variables
			<m> p_1, p_2, \dotsc, p_m </m>.
			If <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are equivalent,
			then so are new statements <m> A' </m> and <m> B' </m> obtained by applying substitution <m> p_i = C_i </m> to <em>both</em> <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>, for every collection of statements <m> C_1, C_2, \dotsc, C_m </m>.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p></statement>

	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p><ol>

		<li>
			Think of <m> X </m> as an intermediate column in the calculation of the truth table of <m> A </m>.
			Replacing <m> X </m> by <m> Y </m> does not change this column,
			as the truth tables of <m> X </m> and <m> Y </m> are the same.
		</li>

		<li>
			We leave this statement for you, the reader, to consider. (Again, think of the <m> C_i </m> as intermediate columns in the calculations of the truth tables of <m> A' </m> and <m> B' </m>.)
		</li>

	</ol></p></proof>

</theorem>

<example><p>
	One of DeMorgan's Laws
	(<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-not-or">Rule</xref>
	of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" />)
	says that <m> \lgcnot (p \lgcor q) \lgcequiv \lgcnot p \lgcand \lgcnot q </m>.
	Therefore,
	<md>
		\lgcnot \bbrac{ (r \lgccond t) \lgcor (t \lgccond r) } \lgcequiv
		\lgcnot (r \lgccond t) \lgcand \lgcnot (t \lgccond r),
	</md>
	using <xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-into-variables">Rule</xref>
	of our new <xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv" text="title" />,
	with substitutions <m> p = r \lgccond t </m>, <m> q = t \lgccond r </m>.
</p></example>

<p>
Here is an example of a string of logical manipulations.
It also demonstrates the use of
<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-cond">Rule</xref>
of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus" />
to manipulate an expression involving a conditional.
</p>

<!--
	TODO does this conflict with some future activity?
	but note that it's referred to in section-proof-methods-cases
-->
<example xml:id="example-logic-equiv-conditional-demorgan">
	<title>DeMorgan with a conditional</title>

	<p>
	Consider the statement <m> (p_1 \lgcor p_2) \lgccond q </m>.
	We may read it as <q>if either <m> p_1 </m> or <m> p_2 </m> is true, then <m> q </m> will be true as well.</q>
	So it seems that each of <m> p_1 </m> and <m> p_2 </m> must imply <m> q </m> on its own.
	Let's see what propositional calculus says about this:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			(p_1 \lgcor p_2) \lgccond q
			\amp \lgcequiv
			\lgcnot (p_1 \lgcor p_2) \lgcor q
			\amp \amp \text{(i)}
		</mrow><mrow>
			\amp \lgcequiv
			(\lgcnot p_1 \lgcand \lgcnot p_2) \lgcor q
			\amp \amp \text{(ii)}
		</mrow><mrow>
			\amp \lgcequiv
			(\lgcnot p_1 \lgcor q ) \lgcand (\lgcnot p_2 \lgcor q)
			\amp \amp \text{(iii)}
		</mrow><mrow>
			\amp \lgcequiv
			(p_1 \lgccond q) \lgcand (p_2 \lgccond q)
			\amp \amp \text{(iv)},
		</mrow>
	</md>
	with justifications
	<ol marker="(i)">

		<li>
			<xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-into-variables">Rule</xref>
			of our new <xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv" text="title" />,
			where we substitute <m> A = p_1 \lgcor p_2 </m> into both sides of the construction of the conditional
			(<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-cond">Rule</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus"/>);
		</li>

		<li>
			<xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-substatements">Rule</xref>
			of our new <xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv" text="title" />,
			using DeMorgan
			(<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-demorgan-not-or">Rule</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus"/>)
			on the substatement <m> \lgcnot (p_1 \lgcor p_2) </m>;
		</li>

		<li>
			distributivity
			(<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-distributivity-right-or-over-and">Rule</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus"/>); and
		</li>

		<li>
			<xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv-substatements">Rule</xref>
			of our new <xref ref="theorem-logic-equiv-subst-equiv" text="title" />,
			using the construction of the conditional
			(<xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus-cond-bicond-cond">Rule</xref>
			of <xref ref="proposition-logic-equiv-rules-prop-calculus"/>)
			on each of the two <q>factors</q> of the conjunction.
		</li>

	</ol>
	So our intuition about the logic of a disjunction in a conditional in this way was correct.
	</p>

	<aside><title>A look ahead</title><p>
		This observation will come in handy <mdash />
		see <xref ref="section-proof-methods-cases" />
		and <xref ref="section-proof-methods-disj" />.
	</p></aside>

</example>

<!-- TODO negating a conditional ? Maybe as an exercise or activity? (Or is it there already?) -->

</section>

<section xml:id="section-logic-equiv-related-conditionals">
<title>Converse, inverse, and contrapositive</title>

<p>
Related to the conditional <m> p \lgccond q </m> are three important variations.
<dl width="narrow">

	<li>
		<title>converse</title>
		<idx>converse</idx>
		<idx><h>conditional</h><h>converse</h></idx>
		<p> <m> q \lgccond p </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>inverse</title>
		<idx><h>inverse</h><h>conditional</h></idx>
		<idx><h>conditional</h><h>inverse</h></idx>
		<p> <m> \lgcnot p \lgccond \lgcnot q </m> </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-logic-equiv-contrapositive">
		<title>contrapositive</title>
		<idx>contrapositive</idx>
		<idx><h>conditional</h><h>contrapositive</h></idx>
		<p> <m> \lgcnot q \lgccond \lgcnot p </m> </p>
	</li>

</dl>
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-logic-equiv-modus-tollens">
	<title>Modus tollens</title>
	<idx>modus tollens</idx>

	<statement><p> A conditional and its contrapositive are equivalent. </p></statement>

	<proof>

		<p> We simply compare the truth tables. </p>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col />
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m> p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot p </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> p\lgccond q </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcnot q \lgccond \lgcnot p </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgcfalse </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
				<cell><m> \lgctrue </m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<p> As the two <q>output</q> columns are identical, we conclude that the statements are equivalent. </p>

	</proof>

</theorem>

<corollary xml:id="corollary-logic-equiv-modus-tollens">
	<title>Modus tollens for inverse and converse</title>

	<statement><p> The inverse and converse of a conditional are equivalent. </p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		The inverse of the conditional <m> p \lgccond q </m> is <m> \lgcnot p \lgccond \lgcnot q </m>.
		The contrapositive of this new conditional is <m> \lgcnot\lgcnot q \lgccond \lgcnot\lgcnot p </m>,
		which is equivalent to <m> q \lgccond p </m> by double negation.
	</p></proof>

</corollary>

<warning>
	<title>Common mistakes</title>

	<p><ul>
		<li> Mixing up a conditional and its converse. </li>
		<li> Assuming that a conditional and its converse are equivalent. </li>
	</ul></p>

</warning>

<example xml:id="example-logic-equiv-related-conditionals">
	<title>Related conditionals are not all equivalent</title>
	<p><ol>

		<li><p>
			Suppose <m> m </m> is a fixed but unspecified whole number that is greater than <m> 2 </m>.
			<dl width="narrow">
				<li><title>conditional</title><p> If <m> m </m> is a prime number, then it is an odd number. </p></li>
				<li><title>contrapositive</title><p> If <m> m </m> is not an odd number, then it is not a prime number. </p></li>
				<li><title>converse</title><p> If <m> m </m> is an odd number, then it is a prime number. </p></li>
				<li><title>inverse</title><p> If <m> m </m> is not a prime number, then it is not an odd number. </p></li>
			</dl>
			Only two of these four statements are true!
		</p></li>

		<li><p>
			Suppose <m> f(x) </m> is a fixed but unspecified function.
			<dl width="narrow">
				<li><title>conditional</title><p> If <m> f </m> is continuous, then it is differentiable. </p></li>
				<li><title>contrapositive</title><p> If <m> f </m> is not differentiable, then it is not continuous. </p></li>
				<li><title>converse</title><p> If <m> f </m> is differentiable, then it is continuous. </p></li>
				<li><title>inverse</title><p> If <m> f </m> is not continuous, then it is not differentiable. </p></li>
			</dl>
			Only two of these four statements are true!
		</p></li>

	</ol></p>
</example>

</section>

